article.description: The Sacramento Monarchs defeated the Houston Comets to clinch the final playoff berth in the Western Conference.
article.headline: Griffith leads Sacramento past Houston
article.linkText: Monarchs clinch last West playoff spot
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Yolanda Griffith picked the perfect
time for her best game of the season.

Griffith scored a season-high 23 points, helping the Sacramento
Monarchs defeat the Houston Comets 68-48 Saturday night and clinch
the final playoff berth in the Western Conference.

The All-Star MVP shot 8-of-10 from the field and 7-of-8 from the
free-throw line in the Monarchs' second victory in three days
against Houston, which missed the playoffs for the first time in
WNBA history.

"Yolanda stepped up, she's done that all season for the
Monarchs, putting them on her back at times," said Houston coach
Van Chancellor, who coached Griffith on the U.S. Olympic team.
"I'm happy for Yolanda and happy for the Monarchs. They deserved
this win tonight."

Sacramento's win eliminated the Phoenix Mercury, who had a
1½-game lead over the Monarchs on Sept. 9 before losing four
straight.

"We were determined in the second half of the season to make
the playoffs," Griffith said. "Now we need to be ready for
whoever we play."

The Monarchs host Minnesota on Sunday night, with the outcome
deciding the two teams' seeding in the postseason.

Sacramento would take the third seed with a win and wins by
Houston and Charlotte. Otherwise, the Lynx will be the No. 3.

Tangela Smith had 12 points, and DeMya Walker scored eight of
her 10 points in the second half when Sacramento gradually pulled
away for an easy victory.

"We held them to 48 points, that's quite an achievement,"
Sacramento coach John Whisenant said. "We struggled offensively at
times, but somewhere in the second half we took control of the
game."

Tina Thompson had 18 points and six rebounds for Houston, but
missed 17 of her 22 shots. Michelle Snow added 12 points and nine
rebounds.

Houston (13-20) played without injured star Sheryl Swoops.

"It's really odd, really tough not making the playoffs for the
first time," Chancellor said. "It's a hollow feeling. ... We were
hurt all year, it's been a rough one."

Griffith scored 11 first-half points, helping the Monarchs take
a 32-27 lead.

Monarchs point guard Ticha Penicheiro sprained her left foot
midway through the first half and did not return.
